revision.text:
The "'''Class of 9/11'''" is a term coined by [[National Public Radio]] for American [[high school]] graduating classes of 2005. These students were [[freshman|freshmen]] when the [[September 11 attacks]] occurred in 2001, and have had to cope with the many aspects of the aftermath during teenage life and high school.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Sept. 11 Shaped the Class of 2005 |first= Susan |last=Stamberg |authorlink= Susan Stamberg |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4656203 |newspaper= |publisher =[[National Public Radio]] |date=May 18, 2005 |accessdate=June 30, 2010 }}</ref> The '''Class of 2002''' can also be considered the Class of 9/11.
This term is now used mainly for the 2005 graduating class of [[United States Military Academy|West Point]], which contained 911 students. According to the [[Associated Press]] report the graduating cadets were told they were "a special group forged by historic events".<ref>{{cite news |title= Joining during peace, cadets graduate in terror's shadow |first=Michael |last=Hill |newspaper= |date=May 29, 2005 |url= }}</ref>
On September 12, 2006, the first member of the class was killed. 2nd Lt. [[Emily Perez]], a Medical Service Corps officer with the [[204th Support Battalion (United States)|204th Support Battalion]], 2nd Brigade, [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]], was leading a platoon when a [[improvised explosive device|roadside bomb]] exploded, killing her. Perez, who had been the highest-ranking black and Hispanic woman in the Academy's history, was the first female West Point graduate to die in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/US/09/26/westpoint.cadet.ap/index.html }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=A Death in the Class of 9/11 |first= Nathan |last=Thornburgh |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date= September 28, 2006 |url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1540856,00.html | accessdate = June 30, 2010 }}</ref>
