{{featured article}}

[[File:The Ezana Stone (2840202630).jpg|thumb|right|300px|alt=The Ezana Stone - This tablet, situated in a field and well below today's ground surface, is believed to have been erected some time during the first half of the fourth century of the current era by King Ezana of Axum in what is now called Ethiopia.|The 4th-century AD [[Ezana Stone]] containing a dual [[Sabaean language|Sabaean]]-style [[Ge'ez script|Ge'ez]] and [[Greek alphabet|Greek]] inscription recording the victories of King [[Ezana of Axum]] over the [[Kingdom of Kush|Kushites]] of [[Meroe]] (in modern [[Sudan]]){{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=276}}]] 
'''Ethiopian historiography''' embodies the [[Ancient literature|ancient]], [[Medieval literature|medieval]], [[Early modern literature|early modern]] and [[History of modern literature|modern]] disciplines of recording the [[history of Ethiopia]], including both native and foreign sources. The roots of Ethiopian historical writing can be traced back to the ancient [[Kingdom of Aksum]] (c. 100 – c. 940 AD). These early texts were written in either the Ethiopian [[Ge'ez script]] or the [[Greek alphabet]], and included a variety of mediums such as [[manuscript]]s and [[Epigraphy|epigraphic]] inscriptions on monumental [[stelae]] and [[obelisk]]s documenting contemporary events. The writing of [[history]] became an established genre in [[Ethiopian literature]] during the early [[Solomonic dynasty]] (1270–1974). In this period, written histories were usually in the form of royal [[biographies]] and dynastic [[chronicle]]s, supplemented by [[Hagiography|hagiographic]] literature and [[Universal history|universal histories]] in the form of [[annal]]s. [[Christian mythology]] became a linchpin of medieval Ethiopian [[historiography]] due to works such as the [[Ethiopian Orthodox|Orthodox]] ''[[Kebra Nagast]]''. This reinforced the genealogical traditions of Ethiopia's Solomonic dynasty [[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles|rulers]], which asserted that they were descendants of [[Solomon]], the legendary [[Kings of Israel and Judah|King of Israel]].

Ethiopian historiographic literature has been traditionally dominated by [[Christian theology]] and the [[chronology of the Bible]]. There was also considerable influence from [[Islam|Muslim]], [[pagan]] and foreign elements from within the [[Horn of Africa]] and beyond. Diplomatic ties with [[Christendom]] were established in the [[Roman Empire|Roman era]] under Ethiopia's first Christian king, [[Ezana of Axum]], in the 4th century AD, and were renewed in the [[Late Middle Ages]] with embassies traveling to and from [[medieval Europe]]. Building on the legacy of ancient [[Greek historiography|Greek]] and [[Roman historiography|Roman]] historical writings about Ethiopia, medieval European chroniclers made attempts to describe Ethiopia, its people, and religious faith in connection to the mythical [[Prester John]], who was viewed as a potential ally against [[History of Islam|Islamic powers]]. Ethiopian history and its peoples were also mentioned in works of medieval [[Historiography of early Islam|Islamic historiography]] and even [[Chinese historiography|Chinese]] [[Chinese encyclopedia|encyclopedias]], [[travel literature]], and [[Official history|official]] [[Twenty-Four Histories|histories]].

During the 16th century and onset of the [[early modern period]], [[military alliance]]s with the [[Portuguese Empire]] were made, the [[Jesuit]] [[Christian mission|Catholic missionaries]] arrived, and prolonged warfare with [[Islam in Africa|Islamic foes]] including the [[Adal Sultanate]] and [[Ottoman Empire]], as well as with the [[polytheistic]] [[Oromo people]], threatened the security of the [[Ethiopian Empire]]. These contacts and conflicts inspired works of [[ethnography]], by authors such as the monk and historian [[Bahrey]], which were embedded into the existing historiographic tradition and encouraged a broader view in historical chronicles for [[Foreign relations of Ethiopia|Ethiopia's place in the world]]. The [[Jesuit missions|Jesuit missionaries]] [[Pedro Páez]] (1564–1622) and [[Manuel de Almeida]] (1580–1646) also composed a history of Ethiopia, but it remained in manuscript form among Jesuit priests of [[Portuguese India]] and was not published in [[Western world|the West]] until modern times.

[[Outline of Ethiopia|Modern Ethiopian]] historiography was developed locally by native Ethiopians as well as by foreign historians, most notably [[Hiob Ludolf]] (1624–1704), the German [[Oriental studies|orientalist]] who British historian [[Edward Ullendorff]] (1920–2011) considered the founder of [[Ethiopian Studies]]. The late 19th and early 20th centuries marked a period where Western historiographic methods were introduced and synthesized with traditionalist practices, embodied by works such as those by [[Heruy Wolde Selassie]] (1878–1938). The discipline has since developed new approaches in studying the nation's past and offered criticism of some traditional [[Semitic languages|Semitic]]-dominated views that have been prevalent, sometimes at the expense of Ethiopia's traditional ties with the [[Middle East]]. [[Marxist historiography]] and [[African studies]] have also played significant roles in developing the discipline. Since the 20th century, historians have given greater consideration to issues of class, gender, and ethnicity. Traditions pertaining mainly to other [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic-speaking]] populations have also been accorded more importance, with literary, linguistic, and archaeological analyses reshaping the perception of their roles in historical Ethiopian society. Historiography of the 20th century focused largely on the [[Abyssinian Crisis]] of 1935 and the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War]], whereas the Ethiopian victory over the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in the 1896 [[Battle of Adwa]] played a major role in the historiographic literature of these two countries immediately following the [[First Italo-Ethiopian War]].

==Ancient origins==
{{further|Dʿmt|King Ezana's Stela|Obelisk of Axum|Aethiopia}}
[[File:Ethio w11.jpg|thumb|alt=Epigraphy in ancient boustrophedon, pre-axoumitic period, found near Aksum - Aksum museum.|An [[Epigraphy|epigraphic]] text in the old [[Ge'ez]] [[Ge'ez script|script]] and ancient [[boustrophedon]], from the period preceding the foundation of the [[Kingdom of Aksum]] (c. 100 AD), found near [[Axum]], Ethiopia]]

Writing was introduced to Ethiopia [[Dʿmt|as far back as the 5th century BC]] with the [[ancient South Arabian script]].{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=375}} This [[South Semitic]] script served as the basis for the creation of Ethiopia's [[Ge'ez]] script, the oldest evidence for it found in [[Matara, Eritrea]], and dated to the 2nd century AD.{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=375}} However, the 1st-century AD [[Latin literature|Roman]] ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' asserts that the local ruler of Adulis could speak and write [[Ancient Greek|in Greek]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=273}} This embrace of [[Hellenization|Hellenism]] could also be found in the [[coin]]age of [[Aksumite currency]], in which legends were usually [[History of the Greek alphabet|written in Greek]], much like [[ancient Greek coinage]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=273}}

===Epigraphy===
The roots of the [[Historiography|historiographic]] tradition in Ethiopia date back to the [[Kingdom of Aksum|Aksumite period]] (c. 100 – c. 940 AD) and are found in [[epigraphic]] texts commissioned by monarchs to recount the deeds of their reign and royal house.  Written in a false [[autobiographical]] style, in either the native [[Ge'ez script]], the [[Greek alphabet]], or both, they are preserved on [[stelae]], [[throne]]s, and [[obelisk]]s found in a wide geographical span that includes [[Sudan]], [[Eritrea]], and [[Ethiopia]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=14–15}} In commemorating the contemporary ruler or aristocrats and elite members of society, these documents record various historical events such as military campaigns, diplomatic missions, and acts of [[philanthropy]]. For instance, 4th-century stelae erected by [[Ezana of Axum]] memorialize his achievements in battle and expansion of the realm in the [[Horn of Africa]], while the ''[[Monumentum Adulitanum]]'' inscribed on a throne in [[Adulis]], Eritrea, contains descriptions of [[Kaleb of Axum]]'s conquests in the [[Red Sea]] region during the 6th century, including parts of the [[Arabian peninsula]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=15}} It is clear that such texts influenced the [[epigraphy]] of later Aksumite rulers who still considered their lost Arabian territories as part of their realm.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=16}}

[[File:Ezana.jpg|thumb|alt=Coin of the Axumite king Ezana.|left|A silver coin of the [[Kingdom of Aksum|Axumite]] [[List of kings of Axum|king]] [[Ezana]], mid-4th century AD]]

In [[Roman historiography]], the [[ecclesiastical]] history of [[Tyrannius Rufinus]], a [[History of Latin|Latin translation]] and extension of the work of [[Eusebius]] dated circa 402, offers an account of the Christian conversion of Ethiopia (labeled as "India ulterior") by the missionary [[Frumentius]] of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|pp=273–274}} The text explains that Frumentius, in order to complete this task, was ordained a bishop by [[Athanasius of Alexandria]] (298–373), most likely after 346 during the latter's third tenure as [[Bishop of Alexandria]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|pp=274–275}} The mission certainly took place before 357, when Athanasius was deposed, replaced by [[George of Cappadocia]], and forced into flight, during which he wrote an apologetic letter to [[Roman emperor]] [[Constantius II]] (r. 337–361) that coincidentally preserved an [[Roman Empire|Imperial Roman]] letter to the royal court of Aksum.{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=275}} In this letter, Constantius II addresses two "tyrants" of Ethiopia, Aizanas and Sazanas, who are undoubtedly Ezana and his brother Saiazana, or Sazanan, a military commander.{{sfnp|Robin|2012|pp=275–276}} The letter also hints that the ruler of Aksum was already a [[Christian monarchy|Christian monarch]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=275}} From the early inscriptions of Ezana's reign it is clear that he was once a [[Polytheism|polytheist]],{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=276}} who erected bronze, silver, and gold statues to [[Ares]], [[List of Greek mythological figures|Greek god of war]].{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=375}} But the dual Greek and [[Sabaean language|Sabaean-style]] Ge'ez inscriptions on the [[Ezana Stone]], commemorating Ezana's conquests of the [[Kingdom of Kush]] (located in [[Nubia]], i.e. modern Sudan), mention his [[conversion to Christianity]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=276}} This claim is supported by the [[Christian symbolism|Christian symbol]] of [[Christian cross|the cross]] decorating virtually all [[Numismatics|Aksumite coins]] minted after Ezana's reign, along with the sudden discontinuation of polytheistic writings.{{sfnp|Robin|2012|pp=275–276}}

{{multiple image|align = right| total_width = 390| image1 = Illumination-from-Abba-Garima-gospel.jpg| width1 = 130 | height1 = | alt1 = Illumination from the Garima Gospels, in a scene depicting Mark the Evangelist.| caption1 = An [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] [[Evangelist portrait]] of [[Mark the Evangelist]], from the Ethiopian [[Garima Gospels]], 6th century AD.| image2 = NothernStelaeField.jpg| width2 = 260 | height2 = | alt2 = "Northern" group of obelisks in Axum.| caption2 = The monumental [[stelae]] and [[obelisk]]s of [[Axum]], Ethiopia, from the [[Kingdom of Aksum|Aksumite period]], 4th century AD.}}
[[Cosmas Indicopleustes]], a 6th-century [[Eastern Roman]] monk and former merchant who wrote the ''[[Christian Topography]]'' (describing the [[Indo-Roman trade relations|Indian Ocean trade]] leading all the way [[Sino-Roman relations|to China]]),{{sfnp|Yule|1915|pp=25, 28}} visited the Aksumite port city of Adulis and included eyewitness accounts of it in his book.{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=372}} He copied a Greek inscription detailing the reign of an early 3rd-century polytheistic ruler of Aksum who sent a naval fleet across the Red Sea to conquer the [[Sabaeans]] in what is now [[Yemen]], along with other parts of western Arabia.{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=372}}{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=277}} Ancient Sabaean texts from Yemen confirm that this was the Aksumite ruler [[GDRT|Gadara]], who made alliances with Sabaean kings, leading to eventual Axumite control over western Yemen that would last until the [[Himyar]]ite ruler [[Shammar Yahri'sh]] (r. c. 265 – c. 287) expelled the Aksumites from southwestern Arabia.{{sfnp|Robin|2012|pp=277–278}} It is only from Sabaean and [[Himyaritic language|Himyarite inscriptions]] that we know the names of several Aksumite kings and princes after Gadara, including the monarchs [[`DBH]] and [[DTWNS]].{{sfnp|Robin|2012|p=278}} Inscriptions of king Ezana mention [[Architecture of Ethiopia|stone-carved thrones]] near the [[Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion]] in [[Axum]] (the platforms of which still exist), and Cosmas described a white-marble throne and stele in Adulis that were both covered in Greek inscriptions.{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=372}}

===Manuscripts===
Aside from epigraphy, Aksumite historiography also includes the [[manuscript]] textual tradition. Some of the earliest Ethiopian [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] manuscripts include translations of the [[Bible]] into Ge'ez, such as the [[Garima Gospels]] that were written between the 4th and 7th centuries and imitated the [[Byzantine art|Byzantine style]] of [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|manuscript art]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=15–16}}{{sfnp|Anfray|2000|p=376}}  The Aksum Collection containing a Ge'ez [[codex]] that provides chronologies for the [[diocese]] and [[episcopal see]]s of the [[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria]] in [[Roman Egypt]] was compiled between the 5th and 7th centuries.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=15–16}} These texts reveal how the Aksumites viewed history through the narrow lens of [[Biblical studies|Christian chronology]], but their early historiography was perhaps also influenced by non-Christian works, such as those from the Kingdom of Kush, the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]] of [[Hellenistic Egypt]], and the [[Yemenite Jews]] of the [[Himyarite Kingdom]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=16}}

==Medieval historiography==
{{further|Ethiopian manuscript collections|Book of Aksum|Giyorgis of Segla|Medieval literature}}
{{multiple image|width1 = 200 |width2= 238 | image1 = Bete Giyorgis 06.jpg| alt1 = Bete Giyorgis (Church of St. George), Lalibela, Ethiopia.| image2 = St. George Astride His Horse, Church of Bet Giorgis, Lalibela, Ethiopia (3268383996).jpg| alt2 = St. George Astride His Horse, Church of Bet Giorgis, Lalibela, Ethiopia.| footer = The [[Church of Saint George, Lalibela]] and a [[panel painting]] inside depicting [[Saint George]] [[St George and the Dragon|slaying a dragon]]; it is one of eleven monumental [[Rock-cut architecture|rock-hewn]] churches built in [[Lalibela]], Ethiopia, allegedly under [[Zagwe dynasty|Zagwe-dynasty]] ruler [[Gebre Mesqel Lalibela]] (r. 1185–1221),{{sfnp|Riches|2015|pp=43–44}}{{sfnp|Sobania|2012|p=462}} while archaeology reveals the [[Architecture of Ethiopia|religious structures]] to have been built between the 10th and early 13th centuries.{{sfnp|Sobania|2012|p=462}}}}

===Zagwe dynasty===
The power of the Aksumite Kingdom declined after the 6th century due to the rise of other regional states in the [[History of the Horn of Africa|Horn of Africa]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=17}} Modern scholars continue to debate the identity and provenance of the legendary or semi-legendary figure [[Gudit]] (fl. 10th century), a queen who is traditionally believed to have overthrown the Kingdom of Aksum.{{sfnp|Augustyniak|2012|pp=16–17}} The legend is found in the 13th-century chronicle of the monk [[Tekle Haymanot]], who compiled historical writings gathered from various [[Christianity in Ethiopia|Ethiopian churches and monasteries]].{{sfnp|Augustyniak|2012|p=16}} The chronicle alleges that, after being exiled from Axum, she married a Jewish king of Syria and converted to [[Judaism]]. The Scottish travel writer [[James Bruce]] (1730–1794) was incredulous about the tale and believed she was simply a Jewish queen.{{sfnp|Augustyniak|2012|p=16}} [[Carlo Conti Rossini]] (1872–1949) hypothesized that she was an ethnic [[Sidama people|Sidamo]] from [[Damot]], whereas [[Steven Kaplan (historian)|Steven Kaplan]] argues she was a non-Christian invader and historian [[Knud Tage Andersen]] contends she was a regular member of the Aksumite royal house who shrewdly seized the throne.{{sfnp|Augustyniak|2012|pp=16–17}} The latter is more in line with another legend that claims [[Dil Na'od]], the last king of Aksum, kept his daughter Mesobe Werq in isolation out of fear of a prophecy that her son would overthrow him, yet she eloped with the nobleman [[Mara Takla Haymanot]] from [[Lasta]] who eventually killed the Aksumite king in a duel, took the throne and founded the [[Zagwe dynasty]].{{sfnp|Augustyniak|2012|p=17}} The latter remains one of the most poorly understood periods of Ethiopia's recorded history.{{sfnp|Riches|2015|p=44}} What is known is that the early Zagwe kings were polytheistic, eventually converted to Christianity, and ruled over the northern [[Highlands of Ethiopia]], while Islamic sultanates inhabited the [[Geography of Ethiopia|coastal Ethiopian Lowlands]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=17}}

===Solomonic dynasty===
[[File:Gebre Mesqel Lalibela.png|thumb|upright|alt=Detail from Ethiopian icon, IESMus3450, showing Negus Lalibela.|A 15th-century [[Ethiopian art|Ethiopian painting]] of the [[Solomonic dynasty]] depicting the [[Zagwe dynasty]] ruler [[Gebre Mesqel Lalibela]] (r. 1181-1221), the subject of a [[Hagiography|hagiographical]] pseudo-[[chronicle]] depicting him as a [[saint]] who performed [[miracle]]s{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=18–19}}]]
When the forces of [[Yekuno Amlak]] (r. 1270–1285) toppled the Zagwe dynasty in 1270 he became the first [[Emperor of Ethiopia]], establishing a line of rulers in the [[Solomonic dynasty]] that would last into the 20th century.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=17}} By this time the [[Greek language]], once pivotal for translation in [[Ethiopian literature]], had become marginalized and mixed with [[Coptic language|Coptic]] and [[Arabic]] translations.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=16–17}} This contributed to a process by which medieval Ethiopian historians created a new historiographic tradition largely divorced from the ancient Aksumite textual corpus.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=16–17}} The Solomonic kings professed a direct link to the kings of Aksum and [[Menelik I|a lineage traced back]] to [[Solomon]] and the [[Queen of Sheba]] in the [[Hebrew Bible]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=17–18}}{{sfnp|Phillipson|2014|pp=66–67}} These genealogical traditions formed the basis of the ''[[Kebra Nagast]]'', a seminal work of Ethiopian literature and Ge'ez-language text originally compiled in Copto-Arabic sometime between the 10th and 13th centuries.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=17–18}}{{sfnp|Phillipson|2014|pp=66–67}} Its current form dates to the 14th century, by which point it included detailed mythological and historical narratives relating to Ethiopia along with [[Christian theology|theological discourses]] on themes in the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]].{{sfnp|Phillipson|2014|p=66}} De Lorenzi compares the tome's mixture of [[Christian mythology]] with historical events to the legend of [[King Arthur]] that was greatly embellished by the Welsh cleric [[Geoffrey of Monmouth]] in his chronicle ''[[Historia Regum Britanniae]]'' of 1136.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=18}} Although the ''Kebra Nagast'' indicates that [[List of Byzantine emperors|the emperors]] of [[Rome]] or [[Constantinople]] and Ethiopia were descended from the [[Israelite]] king Solomon, there is an emphatically [[anti-Jewish]] sentiment expressed in several passages of the book.{{sfnp|Phillipson|2014|p=66}}

The most common form of written history sponsored by the Solomonic royal court was the [[biography]] of contemporary rulers, who were often lauded by their biographers along with the Solomonic dynasty. The royal biographical genre was established during the reign of [[Amda Seyon I]] (r. 1314–1344), whose biography not only recounted the diplomatic exchanges and military conflicts with the rival Islamic powers of the [[Ifat Sultanate]] and [[Adal Sultanate]], but also depicted the Ethiopian ruler as the [[Messiah|Christian savior]] of his nation.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=18}} The origins of the dynastic history (''tarika nagast'') are perhaps found in the biographical [[chronicle]] of [[Baeda Maryam I]] (r. 1468–1478), which provides a narrative of his life and that of his children and was most likely written by the [[preceptor]] of the royal court.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=18}} Teshale Tibebu asserts that Ethiopian court historians were "professional flatterers" of their ruling monarchs, akin to their [[Byzantine literature#Historians and annalists|Byzantine Greek]] and [[Imperial China|Imperial]] [[Chinese historiography|Chinese counterparts]].{{sfnp|Tibebu|1995|p=13}} For instance, the anonymously written biography of the emperor [[Gelawdewos]] (r. 1540–1549) speaks glowingly of the ruler, albeit in an [[elegiac]] tone, while attempting to place him and his deeds within a greater moral and historical context.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=13}}

There are also [[hagiographies]] of previous Zagwe dynastic rulers composed during the Solomonic period. For instance, during the reign of [[Zara Yaqob]] (1434–1468) a chronicle focusing on [[Gebre Mesqel Lalibela]] (r. 1185–1225) portrayed him as a [[Christian saint]] who performed miracles. Conveniently for the legitimacy of the Solomonic dynasty, the chronicle stated that Lalibela did not desire for his heirs to inherit his throne.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=18–19}}

===Medieval Europe and the search for Prester John===
[[File:Prester John.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Image of Prester John, enthroned, in a map of East Africa in Queen Mary's Atlas, Diogo Homem, 1558.|[[Prester John]] as the [[Emperor of Ethiopia]], enthroned on a map of East Africa in an atlas prepared by [[Portuguese Empire|the Portuguese]] for [[Mary I of England]], 1558 ([[British Library]])]]
[[File:Abisynia 1584.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Map of Ethiopia from 1584 by Abraham Ortelius.|A 1584 map of [[Ethiopian Empire|Abyssinia]], by the Flemish cartographer [[Abraham Ortelius]] (1527-1598)]]
In [[Greek historiography]], [[Herodotus]] (484–425 BC) had written brief descriptions of [[Aethiopia|ancient Ethiopians]], who were also mentioned in the New Testament.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|p=19}} Although the [[History of the Byzantine Empire|Byzantine Empire]] maintained [[Byzantine diplomacy|regular relations]] with Ethiopia during the [[Early Middle Ages]], the [[Early Muslim conquests]] of the 7th century severed the connection between Ethiopia and the rest of [[Christendom]].{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|pp=19–21}} Records of these contacts encouraged medieval Europeans to discover if Ethiopia was still Christian or had [[Islamization|converted to Islam]], an idea bolstered by the presence of Ethiopian [[pilgrim]]s in the [[Holy Land]] and [[Jerusalem]] during the [[Crusades]].{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|p=20}} During the [[High Middle Ages]], the [[Mongol conquests]] of [[Genghis Khan]] (r. 1206–1227) led Europeans to speculate about the existence of a priestly, legendary warrior king named [[Prester John]], who was thought to inhabit distant lands in Asia associated with [[Nestorian Christians]] and might help to defeat rival Islamic powers. The [[travel literature]] of [[Marco Polo]] and [[Odoric of Pordenone]] regarding [[Europeans in Medieval China|their separate journeys]] to [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan-dynasty]] [[Foreign relations of Imperial China|China]] during the 13th and 14th centuries, respectively, and fruitless searches in [[southern India]], helped to dispel the notion that Prester John's kingdom existed in Asia.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|pp=16–19}} An Ethiopian diplomatic mission sent to Christian Europe by Ethiopian emperor [[Wedem Arad]] (r. 1299–1314) in 1306 allowed the chance for the priest and [[cartographer]] [[Giovanni da Carignano]] (1250–1329) to question the embassy as they stayed in [[Genoa]], after which he published a work describing the geographic location of their kingdom and the nature of their Christian faith.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|p=22}}

In his 1324 ''Book of Marvels'' the [[Dominican order|Dominican]] missionary [[Jordanus]], bishop of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Quilon]] along the [[Malabar Coast]] of India, was the first known author to suggest that Ethiopia was the location of Prester John's kingdom.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|pp=20–21}} The [[Florence|Florentine]] merchant Antonio Bartoli visited Ethiopia from the 1390s until about 1404 when he returned to Europe with Ethiopian diplomats.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|p=22}} This was followed by the lengthy stay of Pietro Rombuldo in Ethiopia from 1404 to 1444 and Ethiopian diplomats attending the [[Ecumenical council|ecumenical]] [[Council of Florence]] in 1441, where they expressed some vexation with the European attendees who insisted on addressing their emperor as Prester John.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|pp=22–23}} Thanks to the legacy of European medieval historiography, this belief persisted beyond the [[Late Middle Ages]]. For instance, the [[History of Portugal|Portuguese]] missionary [[Francisco Álvares]] set out for Ethiopia in 1520 believing that he was to visit the homeland of Prester John.{{sfnp|Baldridge|2012|p=23}}

===Islamic historiography===
{{further|Historiography of early Islam}}
[[File:YagbeaSionBattlingAdaSultan.JPG|thumb|upright|Yagbea Sion battling the sultan of Ada.|[[Ethiopian Empire|Abyssinian]] King [[Yagbe'u Seyon of Ethiopia|Yagbea-Sion]] and his men (left) battling the Sultan of [[Adal Sultanate|Adal]] and his forces (''[[Le Livre des Merveilles]]'', 15th century).]]
Ethiopia is mentioned in some works of [[Muslim historians|Islamic historiography]], usually in relation to the [[spread of Islam]]. Islamic sources state that in 615 the Aksumite king [[Armah]] (r. 614–631) provided refuge for the exiled followers of [[Muhammad]] in Axum, an event known as the [[First Hejira]] (i.e. [[Migration to Abyssinia]]).{{sfnp|Milkias|2015|p=456}} In his ''History'', the scholar [[Ya'qubi|ibn Wadîh al-Ya'qûbî]] (d. 897) of the [[Abbasid Caliphate]] identified Abyssinia (''al-Habasha'') as being located to the north of the territory of the [[Barbara (region)|Berber]] (Somali) as well as the land of the [[Zanj]] (the "Blacks").{{sfnp|Smidt|2001|p=6}} The [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk-Egyptian]] historian [[Shihab al-Umari]] (1300–1349) wrote that the historical [[Bale Province, Ethiopia|state of Bale]], neighboring the [[Hadiya Sultanate]] of southern Ethiopia, was part of an Islamic [[Zeila]] confederacy, although it fell under the control of the Ethiopian Empire in the 1330s, during the reign of Amda Seyon I.{{sfnp|Braukämper|2004|pp=76–77}} [[Al-Maqrizi]] (1364–1422), another Mamluk-Egyptian historian, wrote that the Ifat sultan [[Sa'ad ad-Din II]] (r. 1387–1415) won a crushing victory against the Christian [[Amhara Province|Amhara]] in Bale, despite the latter's numerical superiority.{{sfnp|Braukämper|2004|p=77}} He described other allegedly significant victories won by the Adal sultan [[Jamal ad-Din II]] (d. 1433) in Bale [[Sultanate of Dawaro|and Dawaro]], where the Muslim leader was said to have taken enough war booty to provide his poorer subjects with multiple slaves.{{sfnp|Braukämper|2004|p=77}} Historian [[Ulrich Braukämper]] states that these works of Islamic historiography, while demonstrating the influence and military presence of the Adal sultanate in southern Ethiopia, tend to overemphasize the importance of military victories that at best led to temporary territorial control in regions such as Bale.{{sfnp|Braukämper|2004|pp=77–78}} In his ''[[Description of Africa (1550 book)|Description of Africa]]'' (1555), the historian [[Leo Africanus]] (c. 1494–1554) of [[Al-Andalus]] described Abassia (Abyssinia) as the realm of the ''Prete Ianni'' (i.e. Prester John), unto whom the Abassins (Abyssinians) were subject. He also identified Abassins as one of five main population groups on the continent alongside [[Africa (Roman province)|Africans]] ([[Moors]]), [[Egyptians]], [[Arabs|Arabians]] and [[Kaffir (racial term)|Cafri]] (Cafates).{{sfnp|Africanus|1896|pp=20, 30}}

===Chinese historiography===
{{further|Chinese historiography|Twenty-Four Histories}}
Contacts between the Ethiopian Empire and [[Imperial China]] seem to have been very limited, if not mostly indirect. There were some attempts in Chinese historiographic and [[Chinese encyclopedia|encyclopedic literature]] to describe parts of Ethiopia or outside areas that it once controlled. Zhang Xiang, a scholar of [[Africa–China relations]], asserts that the country of ''Dou le'' described in the ''Xiyu juan'' (i.e. [[Western Regions]]) chapter of the ''[[Book of Later Han]]'' was that of the Aksumite port city of Adulis.<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African"/> It was from this city that an envoy was sent to [[Luoyang]], the capital of China's [[Han dynasty]], in roughly 100 AD.<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African">Abraham, Curtis. (11 March 2015). "[http://newafricanmagazine.com/chinas-long-history-africa/ China’s long history in Africa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802172711/http://newafricanmagazine.com/chinas-long-history-africa/ |date=2017-08-02 }}". ''[[New African]]''. Retrieved 2 August 2017.</ref> The 11th-century ''[[New Book of Tang]]'' and 14th-century ''[[Wenxian Tongkao]]'' describe the country of Nubia (previously controlled by the Aksumite Kingdom) as a land of deserts [[Diocese of Egypt|south of the Byzantine Empire]] that was infested with [[malaria]], where the natives of the local ''Mo-lin'' territory had [[dark skin|black skin]] and consumed foods such as [[Palm date|Persian dates]].<ref name="hirth 2000"/> In his English translation of this document, [[Friedrich Hirth]] identified ''Mo-lin'' (''Molin'') with the kingdom of [[Alodia|'Alwa]] and neighboring ''Lao-p'o-sa'' with the kingdom of [[Makuria|Maqurra]], both in Nubia.<ref name="hirth 2000">{{cite web|orig-year=1885|year=2000|author=Friedrich Hirth|editor=Jerome S. Arkenberg|url=http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/eastasia/romchin1.html|title=East Asian History Sourcebook: Chinese Accounts of Rome, Byzantium and the Middle East, c. 91 B.C.E. – 1643 C.E. |publisher=[[Fordham University]]|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref> 

The ''Wenxian Tongkao'' describes the [[Islamization of the Sudan region|main religions of Nubia]], including the ''[[Da Qin]]'' religion (i.e. Christianity, particularly [[Church of the East in China|Nestorian Christianity]] associated with [[History of Eastern Orthodox Christian theology|the Eastern Roman Empire]]) and the [[Sabbath|day of rest]] occurring every seven days for those following the faith of the ''Da shi'' (i.e. the [[Islam in Sudan|Muslim Arabs]]).<ref name="hirth 2000"/> These passages are ultimately derived from the ''[[Jingxingji]]'' of [[Du Huan]] (fl. 8th century),{{sfnp|Bai|2003|pp=242–247}} a travel writer during the Chinese [[Tang dynasty]] (618–907) who was captured by [[Sino-Arab relations|Abbasid forces]] in the 751 [[Battle of Talas]], after which he visited parts of [[West Asia]] and [[northeast Africa]].<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African"/> Historian [[Wolbert Smidt]] identified the territory of ''Molin'' in Du's ''Jingxingji'' (preserved in part by the ''[[Tongdian]]'' of [[Du You]]) as the Christian kingdom of Muqurra in Nubia. He also associated the territory of ''Laobosa'' (''Lao-p'o-sa'') depicted therein with Abyssinia, thereby making this the first Chinese text to describe Ethiopia.{{sfnp|Smidt|2001|pp=5–6}}<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African"/> When Du Huan left the region to return home, he did so through the Aksumite port of Adulis.<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African"/> Trade activity between Ethiopia and China during the latter's [[Song dynasty]] (960–1279) seems to be confirmed by [[Ancient Chinese coinage|Song-Chinese coinage]] found in the medieval village of Harla, near [[Dire Dawa]], Ethiopia. The Chinese [[Ming dynasty]] (1368–1644) sent diplomats to Ethiopia, which was also frequented by [[Indian Ocean trade|Chinese merchants]]. Although only private and indirect trade was conducted with African countries during the early [[Manchu]]-led [[Qing dynasty]] (1644–1911), the Chinese were able to refer to Chinese-written travel literature and histories about East Africa before diplomatic relations were restored with African countries in the 19th century.<ref name="Abraham 2015 New African"/>

==Early Modern historiography==
{{further|Ethiopian manuscript collections|Early Modern literature}}
[[File:Books in the monastery museum (5494269533).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Books in the monastery museum of the Orthodox Church of Ura Kidane Mehret, Zege Peninsula, Ethiopia, 16th century.|[[Illuminated manuscript]]s housed in the 16th-century [[Ethiopian Orthodox Church|Orthodox church]] of [[Ura Kidane Mehret]], [[Zege Peninsula]], [[Lake Tana]], Ethiopia]]
[[File:Ethiopian Scroll comprising prayers against various ailments Wellcome L0031387.jpg|thumb|upright|Ethiopian Scroll comprising prayers against various ailments, including chest pains, the expulsion of evil spirits causing sickness and the protection of suckling infants. This illustration shows Susenyos spearing the demon, a popular motif in Ethiopean art similar to St George slaying the dragon.|[[Ethiopian art|A painting]] of [[Susenyos I]] (r. 1607–1632) on horseback spearing a demon (similar to mythical depictions of [[St George]] [[Saint George and the Dragon|slaying a dragon]]), on a [[Ge'ez]] prayer scroll meant to dispel evil spirits that were thought to cause various ailments, [[Wellcome Collection]], London]]

===Conflict and interaction with foreign powers===
During the 16th century the Ethiopian biographical tradition became far more complex, [[Intertextuality|intertextual]], and broader in its view of the world given Ethiopia's direct involvement in [[Ottoman–Portuguese conflicts|the conflicts]] between the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] and [[Portuguese Empire|Portuguese]] empires in the Red Sea region.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=19–20}} The annals of [[Dawit II]] (r. 1508–1540) describe [[Abyssinian–Adal war|the defensive war]] he waged against the Adal sultan [[Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi]] (r. 1527–1543), in an [[Serial (literature)|episodic format]] quite different from the earlier chronicling tradition.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=19}} The chronicle of Gelawdewos, perhaps written by the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Church]] abbot [[Enbaqom]] (1470–1560), is far more detailed than any previous Ethiopian work of history.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=19}} It explains the Ethiopian emperor's [[military alliance]] with [[Cristóvão da Gama]] (1516–1542), son of the [[Portuguese discoveries|Portuguese explorer]] [[Vasco da Gama]], against the Adal Sultan al-Ghazi and his Ottoman allies, and later against the [[Pasha|Ottoman governor]] of [[History of Yemen|Yemen]], [[Özdemir Pasha]] (d. 1560).{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=19–20}}

The biography of Galawdewos' brother and successor [[Menas of Ethiopia]] (r. 1559–1563) is divided into two parts, one dedicated to his life before taking the throne and the other to his troubled reign fighting against rebels.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}} His chronicle was completed by the biographers of his successor [[Sarsa Dengel]] (r. 1563–1597). The latter's chronicle can be considered an [[epic cycle]] for its [[preface]] describing events in previous eras mixed with biblical allusions.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}} It also describes conflicts against rebel nobility allied with the Ottomans as well as a military campaign against [[Ethiopian Jews]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}}

By the 16th century Ethiopian works began to discuss the profound impact of foreign peoples in their own regional history. The chronicle of Gelawdewos explained the friction between the Ethiopian Orthodox Church and the [[Catholic missions|Catholic missionaries]] from [[Spain]] and [[Portugal]], after the arrival of the [[Jesuits]] in 1555.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}} With the persuasion of Jesuits in his realm, emperor [[Susenyos I]] (r. 1607–1632) became the only Ethiopian ruler to [[List of converts to the Catholic Church|convert from Orthodox Christianity to Catholicism]], perhaps earlier than the accepted date of 1625, after which his attempts to convert his subjects and undermine the Orthodox church led to internal revolts.{{sfnp|Abir|1980|pp=211–217}} In 1593 the Ethiopian [[monk]], [[historian]], and [[ethnographer]] [[Bahrey]] published a work of [[ethnography]] that provided reasoning for the military success of the [[Traditional African religions|polytheistic]] [[Oromo people]] who fought against the Ethiopian Empire.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}} Ethiopian histories of this period also included details of foreign [[Muslim]]s, [[History of Judaism|Jews]], [[Christianity|Christians]] (including those from [[Western Europe]]), [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid]] [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]], and even figures of the fallen [[Byzantine Empire]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=20}}
[[File:Ethiopian scribes.jpg|thumb|left|Early 18th century manuscript illumination from Aksum showing two scribes.]]

[[Pedro Paez]] (1564–1622), a [[Spanish Empire|Spanish]] Jesuit at the court of Susenyos I, translated portions of the chronicles of Ethiopian emperors stretching back to the reign of Amda Seyon I in the 14th century AD, as well as the reign of king [[Kaleb of Axum]] in the 6th century AD.{{sfnp|Cohen|2009|pp=106–107}} Some of these fragments were preserved in the ''Historia de Ethiopia'' by the Portuguese Jesuit [[Manuel de Almeida]] (1580–1646),{{sfnp|Cohen|2009|p=106}} but Paez's original manuscript was largely rewritten to remove polemical passages against the rival [[Dominican Order]].{{sfnp|Pennec|2012|pp=83–86, 91–92}} Paez also translated a chapter from an Ethiopian hagiography that covered the life and works of the 13th-century ruler Gebre Mesqel Lalibela.{{sfnp|Cohen|2009|pp=107–108}} The ''Historia de Ethiopia'', which arrived in [[Goa]], India, by the end of 1624, was not published in Europe until the modern era and only remained in circulation among members of the [[Society of Jesus]] in [[Portuguese India]], although Almeida's map of Ethiopia was published by [[Baltasar Teles]] in 1660.{{sfnp|Pennec|2012|pp=87–90, 92–93}} In his treatise ''A Voyage to Abyssinia'', the Portuguese Jesuit missionary [[Jerónimo Lobo]] (1595–1678) described Abyssinia and its denizens, indicating that the native inhabitants were of two distinct physical types: the Abyssinians proper, who were narrow-featured, near olive-skinned, and had long hair which they wore in various styles, and the Soudans, who were [[platyrrhine]] (i.e. flat-nosed), black-skinned, and had woolly hair.{{sfnp|Le Grand|1789|p=198}} Following the [[abdication]] of Susenyos I, his son and successor [[Fasilides]] (r. 1632–1667) had the Jesuits expelled from Ethiopia.{{sfnp|Milkias|2015|p=456}}

===Biographical chronicles and dynastic histories===
At least as far back as the reign of Susenyos I the Ethiopian royal court employed an official court historian known as a ''[[sahafe te'ezaz]]'', who was usually also a senior scholar within the Ethiopian Orthodox Church.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=20–21}} Susenyos I had his [[confessor]] Meherka Dengel and counselor Takla Sellase (d. 1638), nicknamed "Tino", compose his biography.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}} Biographies were written for the emperors [[Yohannes I]] (r. 1667–1682), [[Iyasu I]] (1682–1706), and [[Bakaffa]] (r. 1721–1730), the latter employing four separate court historians: Sinoda, Demetros, Arse, and Hawaryat Krestos.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}} The reigns of the emperors [[Iyasu II]] (r. 1730–1755) and [[Iyoas I]] (r. 1755–1769) were included in general dynastic histories, while the last known royal biography in chronicle format prior to the 19th century was written by the church scholar Gabru and covered the first reign of [[Tekle Giyorgis I]] (r. 1779–1784), the text ending abruptly just before his [[Deposition (politics)|deposition]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}}

==Modern historiography==
{{main|Ethiopian Studies}}
{{further|Modern history|History of modern literature|African studies|Encyclopaedia Aethiopica}}

===Era of the Princes===
{{multiple image|align = right| total_width = 395| image1 = Nerga Sellasie.jpg| width1 = 200 | height1 = | alt1 = Contemporary painting of Mentewab laying prostate at the feet of Mary and Jesus at Närga Selassie.| caption1 = A portrait of the Ethiopian Empress [[Mentewab]], an important figure of the [[Zemene Mesafint]], prostrating herself before Mary and Jesus ([[Narga Selassie]] church, 1748).| image2 = Haile Selassie (1969).jpg| width2 = 195 | height2 = | alt2 = 
Haile Selassie during state visit of Queen Juliana to Ethiopia, January 1969.| caption2 = The Ethiopian emperor [[Haile Selassie]] in 1969; he published his [[autobiography]] ''[[My Life and Ethiopia's Progress]]'' in 1973–1974, shortly before his deposition and the short-lived reign of his son [[Amha Selassie]] in the [[Ethiopian Revolution]].}}
The chaotic period known as the [[Age of the Princes|Era of the Princes]] (Ethiopian: ''[[Zemene Mesafint]]'') from the mid-18th to mid-19th centuries witnessed political fragmentation, civil war, loss of central authority, and, as a result of these, a complete shift away from the royal biography in favor of dynastic histories.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}} A new genre of dynastic history, known as the "Short Chronicle" according to Lorenzi, was established by a church scholar named [[Takla Haymanot (historian)|Takla Haymanot]], whose work combined [[universal history]] with Solomonic dynastic history.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}} The "Short Chronicle" genre of historiography continued well into the 20th century.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=22}} Ge'ez became an [[extinct language]] by the 17th century, but it wasn't until the reign of [[Tewodros II]] (r. 1855–1868) that royal chronicles were [[Vernacular literature|written in the vernacular]] [[Ethiopian Semitic languages|Semitic language of Amharic]].{{sfnp|Milkias|2015|p=474}}

Another genre of history writing produced during the Era of the Princes was the terse Ethiopian [[annal]] known as ''ya'alam tarik''.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=23}} These works attempted to list major world events from the time of [[Book of Genesis|the biblical Genesis]] until their present time in a universal history.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=23}} For instance, the translated work of [[John of Nikiû]] explaining human history until the [[Muslim conquest of Egypt]] in 642 became a canonical text in Ethiopian historiography.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=23}} There are also chronological and [[genealogical]] [[List of Emperors of Ethiopia|lists of rulers]] and [[List of Abunas of Ethiopia|Orthodox Church patriarchs]] that include some elements of historical narrative.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=23}}

===Biographical literature===
Various biographies of Ethiopian emperors have been compiled in the modern era. In 1975 the [[Oxford University|Oxford-educated]] historian [[Zewde Gebre-Sellassie]] (1926–2008) published a biography on the Emperor [[Yohannes II]] (r. 1699–1769), with whom he was distantly related.{{sfnp|Bekerie|2013|p=180}} In 1973 and 1974, the Emperor [[Haile Selassie]] (r. 1930–1974) published his autobiography ''[[My Life and Ethiopia's Progress]]''; in 1976 it was translated from [[Amharic]] into English and [[Annotation|annotated]] by [[Edward Ullendorff]] in an [[Oxford University Press]] publication.{{sfnp|Strang|2013|p=349}} Hanna Rubinkowska maintains that Emperor Selassie was an active proponent of "historiographic manipulation", especially when it came to concealing historical materials that seemingly contested or contradicted dynastic propaganda and [[official history]].{{sfnp|Rubinkowska|2004|pp=223–224}} For instance, he removed certain chronicles and historical works from the public eye and placed them in his private library, such as ''[[aleqa]]'' [[Gabra Igziabiher Elyas]]' (1892–1969) biographical chronicle covering the reigns of Selassie's predecessors [[Iyasu V]] (r. 1913–1916), a late [[Conversion to Islam|convert to Islam]], and the Empress [[Zewditu]] (r. 1916–1930).{{sfnp|Rubinkowska|2004|p=223}}{{sfnp|Omer|1994|p=97}} The latter work was edited, translated into English and republished by [[Rudolf K. Molvaer]] in 1994.{{sfnp|Rubinkowska|2004|p=223, footnote #9}}{{sfnp|Omer|1994|pp=97–102}}

===Ethiopian and Western historiography===
[[File:Aba Gorgorios, 1681.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Portrait of Aba Gorgorios (Abba Gorgoryos) by Elias Christopher Heiss, Augsburg, 1691, in a supplementary volume to the 1681 Historia Aethiopica by Hiob Ludolf.|An engraved book portrait of Ethiopian monk [[Abba Gorgoryos]] (1595-1658) by [[Christopher Elias Heiss]], Augsburg, 1691;<ref>College Library, Special Collections. [https://www.joh.cam.ac.uk/library/special_collections/early_books/pix/ethiopia.htm "Hiob Ludolf, Historia Aethiopica (Frankfurt, 1681)"]. [[St John's College, Cambridge]]. Retrieved 29 July 2017.</ref>{{sfnp|Prichard|1851|p=139}}]]

Edward Ullendorff considered the German [[Oriental studies|orientalist]] [[Hiob Ludolf]] (1624–1704) to be the founder of [[Ethiopian studies]] in Europe, thanks to his efforts in documenting the [[history of Ethiopia]] and the Ge'ez language, as well as Amharic.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|p=1}}{{sfnp|Budge|2014|pp=183–184}} The Ethiopian monk [[Abba Gorgoryos]] (1595–1658), while lobbying the ''[[Propaganda Fide]]'' in Rome to become bishop of Ethiopia following his Catholic conversion and expulsion of the Jesuits by Ethiopian emperor [[Fasilides]], collaborated with Ludolf – who never actually visited Ethiopia – and provided him with critical information for composing his ''Historia Aethiopica'' and its ''Commentaries''.{{sfnp|Salvadore|2012|pp=493–494}}{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|pp=1–2}} The ethnically-Ethiopian Portuguese cleric [[António d'Andrade]] (1610–1670) aided them as a translator,{{sfnp|Salvadore|2012|p=493}} since Abba Gorgoryos was not a fluent speaker of either Latin or Italian.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|p=2}} After Ludolf, the 18th-century Scottish travel writer James Bruce, who visited Ethiopia, and German orientalist [[August Dillmann]] (1823–1894) are also considered pioneers in the field of early Ethiopian studies.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|pp=1–2}}{{sfnp|Budge|2014|pp=184–186}} After spending time at the Ethiopian royal court, Bruce was the first to systematically collect and deposit Ethiopian historical documents into libraries of Europe, in addition to composing a history of Ethiopia based on [[Primary source|native Ethiopian sources]].{{sfnp|Budge|2014|pp=184–185}} Dillmann cataloged a variety of Ethiopian manuscripts, including historical chronicles, and in 1865 published the ''Lexicon Linguae Aethiopicae'', the first such [[lexicon]] to be published on [[languages of Ethiopia]] since Ludolf's work.{{sfnp|Budge|2014|p=186}}

[[File:Thequeenofsheba.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=Nigist (Queen) Makeda of Sheba.|An 1896 depiction of the [[Queen of Sheba]] (Makeda)]]
Ethiopian historians such as [[Taddesse Tamrat]] (1935–2013) and Sergew Hable Sellassie have argued that modern Ethiopian studies were an invention of the 17th century and originated in Europe.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|p=2}} Tamrat considered Carlo Conti Rossini's 1928 ''Storia d'Etiopia'' a groundbreaking work in Ethiopian studies.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|p=2}} The philosopher [[Messay Kebede]] likewise acknowledged the genuine contributions of Western scholars to the understanding of Ethiopia's past.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|pp=2–4}}<ref>College of Arts and Sciences. "[https://udayton.edu/directory/artssciences/philosophy/kebede_messay.php Messay Kebede]" [[University of Dayton]]. Retrieved 28 July 2017.</ref> But he also criticized the perceived scientific and institutional bias that he found to be pervasive in Ethiopian-, African-, and Western-made historiographies on Ethiopia.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|pp=2–4 & 7}} Specifically, Kebede took umbrage at [[E. A. Wallis Budge]]'s translation of the ''Kebra Nagast'', arguing that Budge had assigned a [[South Arabia]]n origin to the Queen of Sheba although the ''Kebra Nagast'' itself did not indicate such a provenience for this fabled ruler. According to Kebede, a South Arabian extraction was contradicted by biblical exegetes and testimonies from ancient historians, which instead indicated that the Queen was of African origin.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|p=4}} Additionally, he chided Budge and Ullendorff for their postulation that the Aksumite civilization was founded by [[Semitic people|Semitic]] immigrants from South Arabia. Kebede argued that there is little physical difference between the Semitic-speaking populations in Ethiopia and neighboring Cushitic-speaking groups to validate the notion that the former groups were essentially descendants of South Arabian settlers, with a separate ancestral origin from other local Afroasiatic-speaking populations. He also observed that these Afroasiatic-speaking populations were heterogeneous, having interbred with each other and also assimilated alien elements of both uncertain extraction and negroid origin.{{sfnp|Kebede|2003|pp=5–7}}

===Synthesis of native and Western historiographic methods===
[[File:Ethiopian 9 Saints Mural Axum.jpg|thumb|alt=The nine saints (not all in photo) of Ethiopian Orthodox Church depicted on the mural in the [[Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion]], Axum, Ethiopia.|Western-style painting of the nine saints (not all in photo) of the Ethiopian Orthodox Church, as depicted on the mural in the Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion, Axum, Ethiopia.]]
During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Ethiopian [[vernacular]] historiography became more heavily influenced by [[Western literature|Western]] methods of historiography, but De Lorenzi contends that these were "[[Indigenization|indigenized]]" to suit the cultural sensibilities of traditionalist historians.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=57–59}} [[Gabra Heywat Baykadan]], a foreign-educated historian and reformist intellectual during the reign of [[Menelik II]] (r. 1889–1913),{{sfnp|Adejumobi|2007|p=59}} was unique among his peers for breaking almost entirely from the traditionalist approach to writing vernacular history and systematically adopting [[Comparative historical research|Western theoretical methods]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=58–59}} [[Heruy Wolde Selassie]] (1878-1938), ''[[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles#Mekwanint|blattengeta]]'' and [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Ethiopia)|foreign minister of Ethiopia]], used [[English literature|English scholarship]] and nominally adopted modern Western methods in writing vernacular history, but he was a firmly traditionalist historian.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=57–59}} His innovative works include a 1922 historical [[dictionary]] that offered a [[prosopography|prosopographic]] study of Ethiopia's historical figures and contemporary notables, a history of Ethiopian foreign relations, historiographic travel literature, and a traditionalist historical treatise combining narrative histories for the Zagwe and Solomonic dynasties with other parts on church history and biographies of church leaders.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=58}}

[[Takla Sadeq Makuriya]] (1913–2000), historian and former head of the [[National Archives and Library of Ethiopia]], wrote various works in Amharic as well as foreign languages, including a four-volume Amharic-language series on the history of Ethiopia from ancient times until the reign of Selassie, published in the 1950s.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=120}} During the 1980s he published a three-volume tome exploring the reigns of 19th-century Ethiopian rulers and the theme of [[Ethiopian nationalism|national unity]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=120}} He also produced two English chapters on the history of the Horn of Africa for [[UNESCO]]'s ''[[General History of Africa]]'' and several French-language works on Ethiopia's church history and royal genealogies.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=120–121}} Some volumes from his [[Vernacular culture|vernacular]] survey on general Ethiopian history have been edited and circulated as school [[textbook]]s in Ethiopian classrooms by the [[Education in Ethiopia|Ministry of Education]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=121}} [[Kebede Michael]] (1916–1998), a playwright, historian, editor, and [[Archaeology of Ethiopia|director of archaeology]] at the National Library, wrote works of [[world history]], histories of [[Western civilization]], and histories of Ethiopia, which, unlike his previous works, formed the central focus of his 1955 world history written in Amharic.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=114–116}}

===Italo-Ethiopian Wars===
[[File:Adua Memorial, or The Folly of Imperialism (3130882917).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Adua Memorial in Adwa, Ethiopia.|An inscribed tomb at the Adua Memorial in the northern town of Adwa, Ethiopia, which commemorates the 1896 [[Battle of Adwa]].]]
The decisive victory of the Ethiopian Empire over the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in the 1896 [[Battle of Adwa]], during the [[First Italo-Ethiopian War]], made a profound impact on the historiography of Italy and Ethiopia.{{sfnp|Forclaz|2015|p=156, note #94}} It was not lost to the [[collective memory]] of Italians, since the Italian capture of [[Adwa]], [[Tigray Region]], Ethiopia in 1935, during the [[Second Italo-Ethiopian War]], was hailed as an act that avenged their previous humiliation and defeat.{{sfnp|Forclaz|2015|p=156}} Historiography about Ethiopia throughout much of the 20th century focused primarily on this second invasion and the [[Abyssinian Crisis]] that preceded it, in which Ethiopia was depicted as being relegated to the role of a pawn in European diplomacy.{{sfnp|Crummey|2000|p=319, note #35}} The Ethiopian [[Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles|courtier (i.e. ''blatta'')]] and historian [[Marse Hazan Walda Qirqo]]s (1899–1978) was commissioned by the Selassie regime to compile a documentary history of the [[Italian Ethiopia|Italian occupation]] entitled ''A Short History of the Five Years of Hardship'', composed concurrently with the submission of historical evidence to the [[United Nations War Crimes Commission]] for [[Yekatit 12|Fascist Italy's war crimes]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=46, 119–120}} Coauthored by [[Berhanu Denque]], this work was one of the first vernacular Amharic histories to cover the Italian colonial period, documenting contemporary newspaper articles and propaganda pieces, events such as the 1936 [[March of the Iron Will|fall of Addis Ababa]] and the 1941 [[East African Campaign (World War II)|British-Ethiopian reconquest of the country]], and speeches by key figures such as Emperor Selassie and [[Rodolfo Graziani]] (1882–1955), [[Viceroy of Italian East Africa|Viceroy]] of [[Italian East Africa]].{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|p=119}}

===Social class, ethnicity, and gender===
{{further|Ethiopian aristocratic and court titles|Social history}}
[[File:Téwodros II.jpg|alt=Tewodros II, around 1860|thumb|upright|Portrait of the Ethiopian Emperor [[Tewodros II]], circa 1860]]
Modern historians have taken new approaches to analyzing both traditional and modern Ethiopian historiography. For instance, [[Donald Crummey]] (1941–2013)<ref>Professor Emeritus of History at the University of Illinois. <br>[[African Studies Association]]. (17 November 2014). "[https://africanstudies.org/individual-membership/in-memory/donald-crummey-1941-2013/ Donald Crummey (1941–2013)]." Retrieved 24 July 2017.</ref> investigated instances in Ethiopian historiography dealing with class, ethnicity, and gender.{{sfnp|Jalata|1996|p=101}} He also criticized earlier approaches made by [[Sylvia Pankhurst]] (1882–1960) and [[Richard Pankhurst (academic)|Richard Pankhurst]] (1927–2017), who focused primarily on the Ethiopian ruling class while ignoring marginalized peoples and minority groups in Ethiopian historical works.{{sfnp|Jalata|1996|p=101}} Following the 1974 [[Ethiopian Revolution]] and overthrow of the Solomonic dynasty with the deposition of Haile Selassie, the [[historical materialism]] of [[Marxist historiography]] came to dominate the academic landscape and understanding of [[Northeast Africa]]n history.{{sfnp|De Lorenzi|2015|pp=11–12, 121–122}} In her 2001 article ''Women in Ethiopian History: A Bibliographic Review'', [[Belete Bizuneh]] remarks that the impact of [[social history]] on African historiography in the 20th century generated an unprecedented focus on the roles of [[Women's studies|women]] and [[Gender studies|gender]] in historical societies, but that Ethiopian historiography seems to have fallen outside the orbit of these historiographic trends.{{sfnp|Bizuneh|2001|pp=7–8}}

By relying on the written works of both Christian and Muslim authors, oral traditions, and modern methods of anthropology, archaeology, and linguistics, [[Mohammed Hassen]], Associate Professor of History at Georgia State University,<ref>College of Arts and Sciences (faculty page). "[http://history.gsu.edu/profile/mohammed-hassen-ali/ Mohammed Hassen Ali: Associate Professor] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804012737/http://history.gsu.edu/profile/mohammed-hassen-ali/ |date=2017-08-04 }}". [[Georgia State University]]. Retrieved 25 July 2017.</ref> asserts that the largely non-Christian [[Oromo language|Oromo people]] have interacted and lived among the [[Semitic languages|Semitic-speaking]] Christian [[Amhara people]] since at least the 14th century, not the 16th century as is commonly accepted in both traditional and recent Ethiopian historiography.{{sfnp|Hassen|2015|pp=ix–xii}} His work also stresses Ethiopia's need to properly integrate its [[List of ethnic groups in Ethiopia|Oromo population]] and the fact that the [[Cushitic languages|Cushitic-speaking]] Oromo, despite their traditional reputation as invaders, were significantly involved in maintaining the cultural, political, and military institutions of the Christian state.{{sfnp|Hassen|2015|pp=x–xi}}

===Middle Eastern versus African studies===
{{further|Middle-Eastern studies|African studies|Egyptian literature|Ancient Egyptian literature}}
[[File:Salama III.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Image of the Abuna Salama, died 25 October 1867.|Engraving of [[Abuna Salama III|Salama III]], head of the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] (1841-1867). This ''[[abuna]]'' (''abun'') ecclesiastical office was established to strengthen Ethiopia's historical ties with the [[Coptic Orthodox Church]] in Egypt.]]
In his 1992 review of [[Naguib Mahfouz]]'s ''The Search'' (1964), the Ethiopian scholar Mulugeta Gudeta observed that Ethiopian and [[History of Egypt|Egyptian societies]] bore striking historical resemblances.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|pp=215–216, 225 note #18}} According to [[Haggai Erlich]], these parallels culminated in the establishment of the Egyptian ''[[Abuna|abun]]'' ecclesiastical office, which exemplified Ethiopia's traditional connection to [[Christianity in Egypt|Egypt]] and [[Christianity in the Middle East|the Middle East]].{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=11}} In the earlier part of the 20th century, Egyptian nationalists also propounded the idea of forming a ''Unity of the Nile Valley'', a territorial union that would include Ethiopia. This objective gradually ebbed due to political tension over control of the [[Nile]] waters.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|pp=5 & 85}} Consequently, after the 1950s, Egyptian scholars adopted a more distant if not apathetic approach to Ethiopian affairs and academic studies.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=216}} For instance, the Fifth Nile 2002 Conference held in [[Addis Ababa]] in 1997 was attended by hundreds of scholars and officials, among whom were 163 Ethiopians and 16 Egyptians.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=11}} By contrast, there were no Egyptian attendees at the Fourteenth International Conference of Ethiopian Studies later held in Addis Ababa in 2000, similar to all previous ICES conferences since the 1960s.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=216}}

Erlich argues that, in deference to their training as [[African studies|Africanists]], native and foreign Ethiopianists of the post-1950 generation focused more on historiographic matters pertaining to Ethiopia's place within the African continent.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=216}} This trend had the effect of marginalizing Ethiopia's traditional bonds with the Middle East in historiographic works.{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=216}} In [[Bahru Zewde]]'s retrospective on Ethiopian historiography published in 2000, he highlighted Ethiopia's ancient tradition of historiography, observing that it dates from at least the fourteenth century and distinguishes the territory from most other areas in Africa.{{sfnp|Zewde|2000|p=5}} He also noted a shift in emphasis in Ethiopian studies away from the field's traditional fixation on Ethiopia's northern Semitic-speaking groups, with an increasing focus on the territory's other [[Afroasiatic languages|Afroasiatic]]-speaking communities. Zewde suggested that this development was made possible by a greater critical usage of oral traditions.{{sfnp|Zewde|2000|p=10}} He offered no survey of Ethiopia's role in [[Middle Eastern studies]] and made no mention of [[Egypt–Ethiopia relations|Egyptian-Ethiopian historical relations]].{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=225, note #19}} Zewde also observed that historiographic studies in Africa were centered on methods and schools that were primarily developed in [[Nigeria]] and [[Tanzania]], and concluded that "the integration of Ethiopian historiography into the African mainstream, a perennial concern, is still far from being achieved to a satisfactory degree."{{sfnp|Erlich|2002|p=225, note #19}}

