'''Morten Richard Ringard''' (18 May 1908 – 1973) was a Norwegian educator and writer.
He was born in [[Holmestrand]]. He spent much of his career in [[Flekkefjord]], from 1942 as a school director.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Morten Richard Ringard|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/Morten_Richard_Ringard|language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 June 2009}}</ref> In the same year he wrote a book on the city history, ''Flekkefjords historie''.<ref>{{cite book|title=En by i verden – en avis i byen|last=Jensen|first=Egil Remi|authorlink=Egil Remi Jensen|date=1997|location=Flekkefjord|page=15}}</ref> In 1952 he wrote the 200-year history of Holmestrand in ''Byen under fjellet''. He biographed [[Hans Seland]], [[Gustaf Fröding]], [[Herman Bang]] and [[Metternich]].<ref>{{cite news|date=16 May 1958|title=Morten Ringard 50 år|first=Gordon|last=Hølmebakk|authorlink=Gordon Hølmebakk|work=Verdens Gang|page=2|language=Norwegian}}</ref> Poetry collections include ''Nattens Sang'' (1931). He was honored with a [[Festschrift]] in 1968.<ref name=snl/>
